# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gene-expression
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] Along with the 28S and 5.8S rRNA in eukaryotes, the **18S rRNA** was early identified as integral structural element of ribosomes which were first characterized by their sedimentation properties and named according to measured Svedberg units.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] Given its ubiquitous presence in eukaryotic life, the evolution of the 18S rRNA was soon proposed as marker for phylogenetic studies to resolve the evolution of eukaryotes.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] The **18S ribosomal RNA** is the structural RNA of the small subunit in the eukaryotic cytoplasmic ribosome.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] The genomic sequence of the 18S rRNA is organized in a group with the 28S and 5.8S rRNA, separated and flanked by the ITS-1, ITS-2 and ETS spacer regions.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] These regions of ribosomal DNA (rDNA) are present with several hundred copies in the active genome, clustered in nucleolus organizer regions (NORs).
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] In ribosome biogenesis, these genes are transcribed together by the RNA polymerase I and are processed in the nucleolus structure of the nucleus.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] The length of the 18S rRNA varies considerably in the eukaryotic phylogenetic tree, corresponding to a range of 16S-19S in Svedberg units, with the average length commonly given as around 2000 nucleotides.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] The 18S rRNA of humans has a length of 1869 nucleotides.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] The universal presence of the **18S rRNA** in eukaryotes and generally high degree of conservation in evolution allow the construction of universal primers for DNA amplification by polymerase chain reaction.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] The possible applications mirror molecular methods involving 16S rRNA of prokaryotes.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] Primers binding in highly conserved regions of the 18S rRNA are an important marker for biodiversity screening, allowing the amplification of unspecified or random targets from environmental samples as well as uncharacterized specimens from collections for DNA sequencing.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] Subsequent sequence alignment covering the less strictly conserved segments then allows the assignment of a sample to biologic clades.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] In the case of 18S rRNA, retrieval of DNA is improved by the abundance of repeating sequences of the rDNA within eukaryotic cells, promoting the sensitivity of the analysis.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] Multiple properties of the genomic sequence of the 18S rRNA have established it as an important marker gene for large-scale phylogenetic analysis and the reconstruction of the metazoan tree of life.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] The integral role in formation and function of the ribosome is a key cause for its omnipresence in eukaryotic life.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] Meanwhile, the gene maintains a high degree of conservation under a persistent selective pressure in all living beings, highlighting its potential for comparison between distantly related clades.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] Early studies utilizing the 18S rRNA sequence constructed the first large-scale phylogenetic trees of the metazoa.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] Evidence from further studies led to the creation of several important clades, such as the Ecdysozoa and Lophotrochozoa.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] During the latter part of the 2000s, and with increased numbers of taxa included into molecular phylogenies, however, two problems became apparent.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] First, there are prevailing sequencing impediments in representatives of certain taxa, such as the mollusk classes Solenogastres and Tryblidia, selected bivalve taxa, and the enigmatic crustacean class Remipedia.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] Failure to obtain 18S sequences of single taxa is considered a common phenomenon but is rarely ever reported.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] Secondly, in contrast to initially high hopes, 18S cannot resolve nodes at all taxonomic levels and its efficacy varies considerably among clades.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] This has been discussed as an effect of rapid ancient radiation within short periods.
[src:gene-expression/18s-rrna] Multigene analyses are currently thought to give more reliable results for tracing deep branching events in Metazoa but 18S still is extensively used in phylogenetic analyses.
[src:gene-expression/2-o-methylation] This modification is able to stabilize the structure of RNA while preventing it from undergoing hydrolysis as the hydroxyl group is replaced.
[src:gene-expression/2-o-methylation] A technique was developed based on this property called RiboMethSeq to quantify the amount of modifications existing in a sample of rRNA.
[src:gene-expression/2-o-methylation] RNA is a short lived molecule and each of the types vary in its longevity in the cell.
[src:gene-expression/2-o-methylation] Ribosomal RNA exists longer in the cell before degradation so utilizing 2'-O-Met would aid in stabilizing its structure.
[src:gene-expression/2-o-methylation] The epitranscriptomics of this particular RNA modification occurs post-translation, causing a change in the resulting protein without the DNA being altered.
[src:gene-expression/2-o-methylation] Having chemical properties intermediate between RNA and DNA, 2'-*O*-methylation is presumed to have been one of the reactive group of RNA molecules on early Earth that would have given rise to DNA.
[src:gene-expression/28s-ribosomal-rna] Combined with 5.8S rRNA to the 5' side, it is the eukaryotic nuclear homologue of the prokaryotic 23S and mitochondrial 16S ribosomal RNAs.
[src:gene-expression/28s-ribosomal-rna] The genes coding for 28S rRNA are referred to as 28S rDNA.
[src:gene-expression/28s-ribosomal-rna] The comparison of the sequences from these genes are sometimes used in molecular analysis to construct phylogenetic trees, for example in protists, fungi, insects, arachnids, tardigrades, and vertebrates.
[src:gene-expression/28s-ribosomal-rna] The 28S rRNA is typically 4000–5000 nt long.
[src:gene-expression/28s-ribosomal-rna] Some eukaryotes cleave 28S rRNA into two parts before assembling both into the ribosome, a phenomenon termed the "hidden break".
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] During or immediately following transcription of pre-rRNA from rDNA in the nucleolus, the ribosomal RNA precursor (pre-rRNA) is modified and associates with a few ribosomal proteins.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Small nucleolar RNAs (snoRNA) dictate the modifications, by base-pairing with target sites in eukaryotic pre-rRNA and may also play a role in pre-rRNA folding.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Pre-rRNA contains external transcribed spacers (5'-ETS, 3'-ETS) at both ends as well as internal transcribed spacers (ITS1, ITS2).
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Cleavages at sites A’ and T1 remove the 5’-ETS and 3’-ETS, respectively.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Cleavages at sites A0, 1 and 2 give rise to 18S rRNA.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Site 3 cleavage can take place before or after cleavage at sites A0, 1, and 2 and may be responsible for the linkage between 18S and 28S rRNA processing pathways.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] The last steps of rRNA processing require cleavages at 3, 4’, 4 and 5 in order to generate mature 5.8S and 28S rRNA.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Research suggests that either simultaneous to or immediately following synthesis of pre-rRNA, internal modifications are made at regions in the rRNA components, 18S, 5.8S, and 28S, which vary depending on cell type.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Xenopus pre-rRNA modifications include ten base methylations, 105 2’-O-methylations of ribose and around 100 pseudouridines while yeast rRNA has merely half of these modifications.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Small nucleolar RNA base-pairs with the pre-rRNA and determines the site of modifications.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Individual snoRNA families perform different modifications.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Box C/D snoRNA guides the formation of 2’-O-Me, while Box H/ACA snoRNA guide the pseudouridines formation.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] There is thought that the base-pairing of snoRNA to pre-rRNA acts as a chaperone in the folding of mature rRNA.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Pre-rRNA comprise three main sizes; 37S (yeast), 40S (Xenopus) and 45S (mammals).
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] In a series of steps, nearly 80 ribosomal proteins assemble with the pre-rRNA.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] During transcription of pre-rRNA, early ribosomal binding proteins associate.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] It is thought that this 30S RNP containing 45S pre-rRNA is the precursor for 80S RNP, which in turn, is the precursor to 55S RNP.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] 55S RNP makes up ~75% of the nucleolar population of pre-ribosomes.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] To form mature rRNA 18S, 5.8S, and 28S, pre-rRNA 40S (Xenopus) and 45S (mammals) must go through a series of cleavages to remove the external and internal spacers (ETS/ITS).
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] This can be done in one of two pathways.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Pathway 1 begins by cleavage at site 3, which separates the 5.8S and 28S rRNA coding regions in 32S pre-RNA from the 18S rRNA coding region in 20S pre-rRNA.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Pathway 2 cleaves at sites A0, 1, and 2 initially, before cleaving at site 3.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] U3 snoRNA, the most abundant snoRNA required for rRNA processing, influences the pathway chosen.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] It associates with pre-rRNA through protein-protein interactions as well as base-pairing.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] To allow the U3 to function properly, base-pairing between the 3’ hinge region of U3 and complementary sequences in the 5’-ETS is required.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] However, pairing between the 5’-hinge of U3 and 5’-ETS may occur but is not necessary for function.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Nucleolin, an abundant phosphoprotein, binds to the pre-rRNA immediately after transcription and facilitates the base-pairing between the U3 snoRNA hinges and the ETS.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] The area where 5’-ETS is cross-linked to U3 is known as site A’, and is sometimes cleaved in a primary processing event in mammalian pre-rRNA.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] The cleavage of this site is dependent on U3, U14, E1 and E3 snoRNAs, and although this cleavage is not a prerequisite for the processing of pre-rRNA, the docking of snoRNP is crucial for 18S rRNA production.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Shortly after the A’ cleavage, the 3’-ETS is cleaved at site T1 by U8 snoRNA.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Subsequent cleaving at sites A0, 1, and 2 requires U3 snoRNA, U14 snoRNA snR30 and snR10 in yeast as well as U22 snoRNA in Xenopus.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] The cleavage of these sites is coordinated to result in a mature 18S rRNA.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] A0 cleavage requires Box A of U3 snoRNA.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] If Box A of U3 is mutated, A0 cleavage is inhibited and while 20S pre-rRNA accumulates it is not processed into 19S rRNA and cleavage at sites and 2 are also inhibited, which suggests that cleavage at A0 precedes that of sites 1 and 2.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] The mechanism for the cleavage of site 1 is not yet known however the position of U3 Box A near site 1 helps to prove that Box A is once again needed for site A1 cleavage.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] However site 2 requires the 3’-end of BoxA’ and U3 snoRNA for cleavage.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Once site 2 is cleaved, 18S rRNA is liberated from the pre-rRNA.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Whereas U3 snoRNA is required for 18S rRNA formation, U8 snoRNA is required for 5.8S and 28S rRNA formation.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] The cleavage occurs at site 3, which is near the end of ITS1 and subsequently forms 32S pre-rRNA, a long-lived intermediate.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Cleavage at site 4’, within ITS2, produces a precursor of 5.8S RNA that is longer at its 3’-end.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] To trim the 3’-end, cleavage must occur at sites 4 and 5.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] It is hypothesized that site 3 may serve as a link between 18S and 28S rRNA processing pathways in higher organisms.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Pre-rRNA in all of biological kingdoms show similarities and differences.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] Eubacteria contain 16S and 23S rRNA that reside at the top of long base-paired stems that serve as the site for processing of RNase III cleavage.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] These two stems are also found in pre-rRNA from archaebacteria, however they do not exist in Xenopus pre-rRNA.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] It is thought that while base-pairing occurs in all types of pre-rRNA, they occur in cis in eubacterial pre-rRNA, whereas in eukaryotes it occurs in trans between snoRNAs and the termini of the rRNA coding regions in pre-rRNA.
[src:gene-expression/45s-pre-rrna] It is not fully clear why all three kingdoms possess pre-rRNA, rather than directly transcribing mature forms of rRNA, but it is believed that the transcribed spaces in the pre-rRNA may have some type of role in the proper folding of rRNA.
[src:gene-expression/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] In molecular biology, the **5.8S ribosomal RNA** (**5.8S rRNA**) is a non-coding RNA component of the large subunit of the eukaryotic ribosome and so plays an important role in protein translation.
[src:gene-expression/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] It is transcribed by RNA polymerase I as part of the 45S precursor that also contains 18S and 28S rRNA.
[src:gene-expression/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] Its function is thought to be in ribosome translocation.
[src:gene-expression/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] It is also known to form covalent linkage to the p53 tumour suppressor protein.
[src:gene-expression/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] 5.8S rRNA can be used as a reference gene for miRNA detection.
[src:gene-expression/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The 5.8S ribosomal RNA is used to better understand other rRNA processes and pathways in the cell.
[src:gene-expression/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The 5.8S rRNA is homologous to the 5' end of non-eukaryotic LSU rRNA.
[src:gene-expression/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] In eukaryotes, the insertion of ITS2 breaks LSU rRNA into 5.8S and 28S rRNAs.
[src:gene-expression/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] Some flies have their 5.8 rRNA further split into two pieces at the 3' end, forming what is called 5.8S, ITS2a, and 2S.
[src:gene-expression/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] L567.5 rRNA structure is approximately 150 nucleotides in size and it consists of plenty of folded strands, some of which are presumed to be single stranded.
[src:gene-expression/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] This ribosomal RNA, along with the 28S and 5S rRNA as well as 46 ribosomal proteins, forms the ribosomal large subunit (LSU).
[src:gene-expression/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The 5.8S rRNA is initially transcribed along with the 18S and 28S rRNA in the 45S preribosomal RNA, along with the ITS 1 and ITS 2 (Internal transcribed spacer) and a 5’ and 3’ ETS (External transcribed spacer).
[src:gene-expression/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The 5.8S rRNA is located between the two ITS regions, with ITS1 separating it from the 18S rRNA in the 5' direction, and ITS2 separating it from the 28S rRNA in the 3' direction.
[src:gene-expression/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The ITS and ETS are cleaved away during rRNA maturation.
[src:gene-expression/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] This is accomplished through a continuous cleavage pathway performed by both endonuclease and exonuclease enzymes, cutting the spacers at specific locations.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] In molecular biology, the **five-prime cap** (**5′ cap**) is a specially altered nucleotide on the 5′ end of some primary transcripts such as precursor messenger RNA.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] In eukaryotes, the main form is **mRNA capping**, a highly regulated process that uses 7-methylguanosine, vital in the creation of stable and mature messenger RNA able to undergo translation during protein synthesis.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Mitochondrial mRNA and chloroplastic mRNA are not capped.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] When an RNA is made by a RNA polymerase (RNAP), it has a triphosphate group on its 5' end due to the use of nucleoside triphosphates (NTP, pppN) by the RNAP.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] In eukaryotes, the exposed ppp end is "capped" by a guanine soon after it is freed from the RNAP, forming the 5' cap.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Due to how it formed, the cap connects to mRNA via an unusual 5′ to 5′ triphosphate linkage.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] This guanosine is methylated on the 7 position directly after capping *in vivo* by a methyltransferase.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] The result is a 7-methylguanylate (m7G) cap.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Cap-0, mRNA with only the m7G cap, is the basic cap structure for eukaryotic mRNA.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Its structure is written as m7GpppN: m7G, connected to a string of three phosphate groups, then to any other nucleotide.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] The first and second transcribed nucleotides can also be 2' O-methylated (N → Nm), leading to the Cap-1 and Cap-2 structures, respectively.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Cap-1 has a methylated 2′-hydroxy group on the first ribose sugar[m7G ppp Nm-], while cap-2 has methylated 2′-hydroxy groups on the first two ribose sugars [m7G ppp Nm p Nm-], shown on the right.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] This is more common in higher eukaryotes and thought to be part of the innate immune system to recognize mRNAs from other organisms.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] The choice of whether to make these modifications vary by organism and the starting bases of the mRNA.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] This strategy is also adopted by some viruses that infect eukaryotes.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] In all organisms, mRNA molecules can be decapped in a process known as messenger RNA decapping.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] This is usually followed by degradation of the mRNA.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] The starting point for capping with 7-methylguanylate is the unaltered 5′ end of an RNA molecule, which terminates at a triphosphate group.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] This features a final nucleotide followed by three phosphate groups attached to the 5′ carbon.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] The capping process is initiated before the completion of transcription, as the nascent pre-mRNA (ppp(-5′)N[pN]n) is being synthesized.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] GTP is added to the terminal bisphosphate by mRNA guanylyltransferase (GTase), losing a pyrophosphate from the GTP substrate in the process.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] The above describes the canonical capping process involving a TPase, GTase, and a MTase, arriving at Cap-0.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Cap-1 and Cap-2 can be produced from Cap-0 with 2'-O-methylation by a mRNA (nucleoside-2'-O-)-methyltransferase (2'-O-MTase).
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Further modification is also possible: for example, if the nearest cap-adjacent nucleotide is 2′-*O*-ribose methyl-adenosine (i.e.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] (m7G)ppp(Am)[pN]n), it can be further methylated at the N6 methyl position to form *N*6-methyladenosine, resulting in 5′(m7G)ppp(N6Am)[pN]n.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] For capping with 7-methylguanylate, the capping enzyme complex (CEC) binds to RNA polymerase II before transcription starts.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] As soon as the 5′ end of the new transcript emerges from RNA polymerase II, the CEC carries out the capping process (this kind of mechanism ensures capping, as with polyadenylation).
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] The enzymes for capping can only bind to RNA polymerase II, ensuring specificity to only these transcripts, which are almost entirely mRNA.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Promotion of 5′ proximal intron excision.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Nuclear export of RNA is regulated by the cap binding complex (CBC), which binds exclusively to 7-methylguanylate-capped RNA.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] The CBC is then recognized by the nuclear pore complex and exported.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Once in the cytoplasm after the pioneer round of translation, the CBC is replaced by the translation factors eIF4E and eIF4G of the eIF4F complex.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] This complex is then recognized by other translation initiation machinery including the ribosome.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Capping with 7-methylguanylate prevents 5′ degradation in multiple ways.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] First, degradation of the mRNA by 5′ exonucleases (which are abundant in the nucleus) is prevented by chemically looking like a 3′ end.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Second, the CBC and eIF4E/eIF4G block the access of decapping enzymes to the cap.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Additional cap-binding proteins also contribute.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] This increases the half-life of the mRNA, essential in eukaryotes as the export and translation processes take significant time.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] The mechanism of 5′ proximal intron excision promotion is not well understood, but the 7-methylguanylate cap appears to loop around and interact with the spliceosome in the splicing process, promoting intron excision.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Decapping of a 7-methylguanylate-capped mRNA is catalyzed by the decapping complex made up of at least Dcp1 and Dcp2, which must compete with eIF4E to bind the cap.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Thus the 7-methylguanylate cap is a marker of an actively translating mRNA and is used by cells to regulate mRNA half-lives in response to new stimuli.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Undesirable mRNAs are sent to P-bodies for temporary storage or decapping, the details of which are still being resolved.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] The corresponding enzyme activity is m7G(5')pppN diphosphatase, which produces the products m7Gp and ppN-RNA.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Viruses that infect eukaryotes employ a variety of stretegies to form caps that the host would recognize.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Some encode the canonical trio of enzymes, occasionally in combination with a 2'-O-MTase (e.g. vaccinia virus).
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] There are also ones that use more different options.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] For example, picornavirus has its RdRP build RNAs starting with a protein, which acts as a cap.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] In addition, some of the Mimiviridae carry a variant of eIF4F for their own use.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] The viral version specifically recognizes m7GpppAm-mRNA, the kind made by other viral proteins, and is not downregulated in times of stress like the host version.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Eukaryotic small nuclear RNAs contain unique 5′-caps.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Sm-class snRNAs are found with 2,2,7-trimethylguanosine (m3G) caps, while Lsm-class snRNAs are found with monomethyl caps.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Both are linked to the 5' end of the RNA via a triphosphate (ppp) linkage (in 5'-5' orientation in the case of m3G), like the mRNA cap.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] In bacteria, and potentially also in higher organisms, some RNAs are capped with NAD+, NADH, or 3′-dephospho-coenzyme A (dpCoA).
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Unlike the eukaryotic caps, the bacterial caps are linked to 5' end of the RNA using a regular monophosphate (p) linkage; they internally contain a diphosphate linkage, however.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] The mechanism of capping with NAD(+/H) or dpCoA is different.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Capping with these groups is accomplished through an "ab initio capping mechanism," in which NAD(+/H) or dpCoA serves as a "non-canonical initiating nucleotide" (NCIN) for transcription initiation by RNA polymerase and thereby directly is incorporated into the RNA product.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] This is due to their structual similarity with ATP.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Both bacterial RNA polymerase and eukaryotic RNA polymerase II are able to carry out this "ab initio capping mechanism" *in vitro*.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] Capping with NAD(+/H) or dpCoA is targeted by promoter sequence.
[src:gene-expression/5-cap] NCIN capping occurs only at promoters that have certain sequences at and immediately upstream of the transcription start site and therefore occurs only for RNAs synthesized from certain promoters.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] The **5S ribosomal RNA** (**5S rRNA**) is an approximately 120 nucleotide-long ribosomal RNA molecule with a mass of 40 kDa.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] It is a structural and functional component of the large subunit of the ribosome in all domains of life (bacteria, archaea, and eukaryotes), with the exception of mitochondrial ribosomes of fungi and animals.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] The designation 5S refers to the molecule's sedimentation coefficient in an ultracentrifuge, which is measured in Svedberg units (S).
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] In prokaryotes, the 5S rRNA gene is typically located in the rRNA operons downstream of the small and the large subunit rRNA, and co-transcribed into a polycistronic precursor.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] A particularity of eukaryotic nuclear genomes is the occurrence of multiple 5S rRNA gene copies (5S rDNA) clustered in tandem repeats, with copy number varying from species to species.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] Eukaryotic 5S rRNA is synthesized by RNA polymerase III, whereas other eukaryotic rRNAs are cleaved from a 45S precursor transcribed by RNA polymerase I.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] In *Xenopus* oocytes, it has been shown that fingers 4–7 of the nine-zinc finger transcription factor TFIIIA can bind to the central region of 5S RNA.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] Binding between 5S rRNA and TFIIIA serves to both repress further transcription of the 5S RNA gene and stabilize the 5S RNA transcript until it is required for ribosome assembly.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] The secondary structure of 5S rRNA consists of five helices (denoted I–V in roman numerals), four loops (B-E), and one hinge (A), which form together a Y-like structure.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] Loops C and D are terminal hairpins and loops B and E are internal.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] According to phylogenetic studies, helices I and III are likely ancestral.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] Helix III includes two highly conserved adenosines.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] Helix V, with its hairpin structure, is thought to interact with TFIIIA.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] Using a variety of molecular techniques, including immuno-electron microscopy, cryo-electron microscopy, intermolecular chemical cross-linking, and X-ray crystallography, the location of the 5S rRNA within the large ribosomal subunit has been determined to great precision.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] In bacteria and archaea, the large ribosomal subunit (LSU) itself is composed of two RNA moieties, the 5S rRNA and another larger RNA known as 23S rRNA, along with numerous associated proteins.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] In eukaryotes, the LSU contains 5S, 5.8S, and 28S rRNAs and even more proteins.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] The structure of LSU in 3-dimensions shows one relatively smooth surface and the opposite surface having three projections, notably the L1 protuberance, the central protuberance (CP), and the L7/L12 stalk.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] The L1 protuberance and L7/L12 stalk are arranged laterally surrounding CP.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] The 5S rRNA is located in the CP and participates in formation and structure of this projection.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] The other major constituents of the central protuberance include the 23S rRNA (or alternatively 28S in eukaryotes) and several proteins including L5, L18, L25, and L27.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] The exact function of 5S rRNA is not yet clear.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] In *Escherichia coli*, 5S rRNA gene deletions reduce the protein synthesis rate and have a more profound detrimental effect on cell fitness than deletions of a comparable number of copies of other (16S and 23S) rRNA genes.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] Crystallographic studies indicate that 5S rRNA-binding proteins and other proteins of the central protuberance of the LSU plays a role in binding tRNAs.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] In eukaryotes, the cytosolic ribosome is assembled from four rRNAs and over 80 proteins.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] Once transcribed, the 3' ends of 5S rRNA can only be trimmed to mature length by functional homologues of RNase T, for example Rex1p in *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] The 60S and 40S ribosomal subunits are exported from the nucleus to the cytoplasm where they join to form the mature and translation-competent 80S ribosome.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] When exactly 5S rRNA is integrated into the ribosome remains controversial, but it is generally accepted that 5S rRNA is incorporated into the 90S particle, which is a precursor to 60S particle, as part of a small ribosome-independent RNP complex formed by 5S rRNA and ribosomal protein L5.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] Several important proteins which interact with 5S rRNA are listed below.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] Interaction of 5S rRNA with the La protein prevents the RNA from degradation by exonucleases in the cell.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] La protein is found in the nucleus in all eukaryotic organisms and associates with several types of RNAs transcribed by RNA pol III.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] La protein interacts with these RNAs (including the 5S rRNA) through their 3' oligo-uridine tract, aiding stability and folding of the RNA.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] In eukaryotic cells, ribosomal protein L5 associates and stabilizes the 5S rRNA forming a pre-ribosomal ribonucleoprotein particle (RNP) that is found in both cytosol and the nucleus.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] L5 deficiency prevents transport of 5S rRNA to the nucleus and results in decreased ribosomal assembly.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] In prokaryotes the 5S rRNA binds to the L5, L18 and L25 ribosomal proteins, whereas in eukaryotes 5S rRNA is only known to bind the L5 ribosomal protein.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] In *T. brucei*, the causative agent of sleeping sickness, 5S rRNA interacts with two closely related RNA-binding proteins, P34 and P37, whose loss results in a lower global level of 5S rRNA.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] Translation machineries of mitochondria and plastids (organelles of endosymbiotic bacterial origin), and their bacterial relatives share many features but also display marked differences.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] Organelle genomes encode SSU and LSU rRNAs without exception, yet the distribution of 5S rRNA genes (*rrn5*) is most uneven.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] *Rrn5* is easily identified and common in genomes of most plastids.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] In contrast, mitochondrial *rrn5* initially appeared to be restricted to plants and a small number of protists.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] Additional, more divergent organellar 5S rRNAs were only identified with specialized covariance models that incorporate information on the pronounced sequence composition bias and structural variation.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] This analysis pinpointed additional 5S rRNA genes not only in mitochondrial genomes of most protist lineages, but also in genomes of certain apicoplasts (non-photosynthetic plastids of pathogenic protozoa such as *Toxoplasma gondii* and *Eimeria tenella*).
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] Mitochondrial 5S rRNAs of most stramenopiles comprise the largest diversity of secondary structures.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] The permuted mitochondrial 5S rRNAs in brown algae represent the most unconventional case, where the closing helix I, which otherwise brings together the molecule's 5′ and 3′ ends, is replaced by a (closed) hairpin resulting in an open three-way junction.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] Current evidence indicates that mitochondrial DNA of only a few groups, notably animals, fungi, alveolates and euglenozoans lacks the gene.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] The central protuberance, otherwise occupied by 5S rRNA and its associated proteins (see **Figure 2**), was remodeled in various ways.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] In the fungal mitochondrial ribosomes, 5S rRNA is replaced by LSU rRNA expansion sequences.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] In kinetoplastids (euglenozoans), the central protuberance is made entirely of evolutionarily novel mitochondrial ribosomal proteins.
[src:gene-expression/5s-rrna] Lastly, animal mitochondrial ribosomes have coopted a specific mitochondrial tRNA (Val in vertebrates) to substitute the missing 5S rRNA.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The production of a RNA copy from a DNA strand is called transcription, and is performed by RNA polymerases, which add one ribonucleotide at a time to a growing RNA strand as per the complementarity law of the nucleotide bases.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] This RNA is complementary to the template 3′ → 5′ DNA strand, with the exception that thymines (T) are replaced with uracils (U) in the RNA and possible errors.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In bacteria, transcription is carried out by a single type of RNA polymerase, which needs to bind a DNA sequence called a Pribnow box with the help of the sigma factor protein (σ factor) to start transcription.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In eukaryotes, transcription is performed in the nucleus by three types of RNA polymerases, each of which needs a special DNA sequence called the promoter and a set of DNA-binding proteins—transcription factors—to initiate the process (see regulation of transcription below).
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] RNA polymerase I is responsible for transcription of ribosomal RNA (rRNA) genes.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] RNA polymerase II (Pol II) transcribes all protein-coding genes but also some non-coding RNAs (*e.g.*, snRNAs, snoRNAs or long non-coding RNAs).
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] RNA polymerase III transcribes 5S rRNA, transfer RNA (tRNA) genes, and some small non-coding RNAs (*e.g.*, 7SK).
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Transcription ends when the polymerase encounters a sequence called the terminator.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] While transcription of prokaryotic protein-coding genes creates messenger RNA (mRNA) that is ready for translation into protein, transcription of eukaryotic genes leaves a primary transcript of RNA (pre-RNA), which first has to undergo a series of modifications to become a mature RNA.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Types and steps involved in the maturation processes vary between coding and non-coding preRNAs; *i.e.* even though preRNA molecules for both mRNA and tRNA undergo splicing, the steps and machinery involved are different.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The processing of non-coding RNA is described below (non-coding RNA maturation).
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The processing of pre-mRNA include 5′ *capping*, which is set of enzymatic reactions that add 7-methylguanosine (m7G) to the 5′ end of pre-mRNA and thus protect the RNA from degradation by exonucleases.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The m7G cap is then bound by cap binding complex heterodimer (CBP20/CBP80), which aids in mRNA export to cytoplasm and also protect the RNA from decapping.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Another modification is 3′ *cleavage and polyadenylation*.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] They occur if polyadenylation signal sequence (5′- AAUAAA-3′) is present in pre-mRNA, which is usually between protein-coding sequence and terminator.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The pre-mRNA is first cleaved and then a series of ~200 adenines (A) are added to form poly(A) tail, which protects the RNA from degradation.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The poly(A) tail is bound by multiple poly(A)-binding proteins (PABPs) necessary for mRNA export and translation re-initiation.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In the inverse process of deadenylation, poly(A) tails are shortened by the CCR4-Not 3′-5′ exonuclease, which often leads to full transcript decay.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] A very important modification of eukaryotic pre-mRNA is *RNA splicing*.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The majority of eukaryotic pre-mRNAs consist of alternating segments called exons and introns.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] During the process of splicing, an RNA-protein catalytical complex known as spliceosome catalyzes two transesterification reactions, which remove an intron and release it in form of lariat structure, and then splice neighbouring exons together.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In certain cases, some introns or exons can be either removed or retained in mature mRNA.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] This so-called alternative splicing creates series of different transcripts originating from a single gene.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Because these transcripts can be potentially translated into different proteins, splicing extends the complexity of eukaryotic gene expression and the size of a species proteome.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Extensive RNA processing may be an evolutionary advantage made possible by the nucleus of eukaryotes.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In prokaryotes, transcription and translation happen together, whilst in eukaryotes, the nuclear membrane separates the two processes, giving time for RNA processing to occur.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In most organisms non-coding genes (ncRNA) are transcribed as precursors that undergo further processing.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In the case of ribosomal RNAs (rRNA), they are often transcribed as a pre-rRNA that contains one or more rRNAs.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The pre-rRNA is cleaved and modified (2′-*O*-methylation and pseudouridine formation) at specific sites by approximately 150 different small nucleolus-restricted RNA species, called snoRNAs.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] SnoRNAs associate with proteins, forming snoRNPs.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] While snoRNA part basepair with the target RNA and thus position the modification at a precise site, the protein part performs the catalytical reaction.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In eukaryotes, in particular a snoRNP called RNase, MRP cleaves the 45S pre-rRNA into the 28S, 5.8S, and 18S rRNAs.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The rRNA and RNA processing factors form large aggregates called the nucleolus.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In the case of transfer RNA (tRNA), for example, the 5′ sequence is removed by RNase P, whereas the 3′ end is removed by the tRNase Z enzyme and the non-templated 3′ CCA tail is added by a nucleotidyl transferase.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In the case of micro RNA (miRNA), miRNAs are first transcribed as primary transcripts or pri-miRNA with a cap and poly-A tail and processed to short, 70-nucleotide stem-loop structures known as pre-miRNA in the cell nucleus by the enzymes Drosha and Pasha.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] After being exported, it is then processed to mature miRNAs in the cytoplasm by interaction with the endonuclease Dicer, which also initiates the formation of the RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC), composed of the Argonaute protein.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Even snRNAs and snoRNAs themselves undergo series of modification before they become part of functional RNP complex.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] This is done either in the nucleoplasm or in the specialized compartments called Cajal bodies.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Their bases are methylated or pseudouridinilated by a group of small Cajal body-specific RNAs (scaRNAs), which are structurally similar to snoRNAs.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] For some non-coding RNA, the mature RNA is the final gene product.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In the case of messenger RNA (mRNA) the RNA is an information carrier coding for the synthesis of one or more proteins. mRNA carrying a single protein sequence (common in eukaryotes) is monocistronic whilst mRNA carrying multiple protein sequences (common in prokaryotes) is known as polycistronic.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Every mRNA consists of three parts: a 5′ untranslated region (5′UTR), a protein-coding region or open reading frame (ORF), and a 3′ untranslated region (3′UTR).
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The coding region carries information for protein synthesis encoded by the genetic code to form triplets.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Each triplet of nucleotides of the coding region is called a codon and corresponds to a binding site complementary to an anticodon triplet in transfer RNA.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Transfer RNAs with the same anticodon sequence always carry an identical type of amino acid.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Amino acids are then chained together by the ribosome according to the order of triplets in the coding region.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The ribosome helps transfer RNA to bind to messenger RNA and takes the amino acid from each transfer RNA and makes a structure-less protein out of it.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Each mRNA molecule is translated into many protein molecules, on average ~2800 in mammals.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In prokaryotes translation generally occurs at the point of transcription (co-transcriptionally), often using a messenger RNA that is still in the process of being created.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In eukaryotes translation can occur in a variety of regions of the cell depending on where the protein being written is supposed to be.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Major locations are the cytoplasm for soluble cytoplasmic proteins and the membrane of the endoplasmic reticulum for proteins that are for export from the cell or insertion into a cell membrane.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Proteins that are supposed to be produced at the endoplasmic reticulum are recognised part-way through the translation process.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] This is governed by the signal recognition particle—a protein that binds to the ribosome and directs it to the endoplasmic reticulum when it finds a signal peptide on the growing (nascent) amino acid chain.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Regulation of gene expression is the control of the amount and timing of appearance of the functional product of a gene.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Control of expression is vital to allow a cell to produce the gene products it needs when it needs them; in turn, this gives cells the flexibility to adapt to a variable environment, external signals, damage to the cell, and other stimuli.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] More generally, gene regulation gives the cell control over all structure and function, and is the basis for cellular differentiation, morphogenesis and the versatility and adaptability of any organism.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Any step of gene expression may be modulated, from the DNA-RNA transcription step to post-translational modification of a protein.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The stability of the final gene product, whether it is RNA or protein, also contributes to the expression level of the gene—an unstable product results in a low expression level.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In general gene expression is regulated through changes in the number and type of interactions between molecules that collectively influence transcription of DNA and translation of RNA.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Direct interaction with DNA is the simplest and the most direct method by which a protein changes transcription levels.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Genes often have several protein binding sites around the coding region with the specific function of regulating transcription.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] There are many classes of regulatory DNA binding sites known as enhancers, insulators and silencers.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The mechanisms for regulating transcription are varied, from blocking key binding sites on the DNA for RNA polymerase to acting as an activator and promoting transcription by assisting RNA polymerase binding.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The activity of transcription factors is further modulated by intracellular signals causing protein post-translational modification including phosphorylation, acetylation, or glycosylation.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] These changes influence a transcription factor's ability to bind, directly or indirectly, to promoter DNA, to recruit RNA polymerase, or to favor elongation of a newly synthesized RNA molecule.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The nuclear membrane in eukaryotes allows further regulation of transcription factors by the duration of their presence in the nucleus, which is regulated by reversible changes in their structure and by binding of other proteins.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Environmental stimuli or endocrine signals may cause modification of regulatory proteins eliciting cascades of intracellular signals, which result in regulation of gene expression.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] It has become apparent that there is a significant influence of non-DNA-sequence specific effects on transcription.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] These effects are referred to as epigenetic and involve the higher order structure of DNA, non-sequence specific DNA binding proteins and chemical modification of DNA.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In general epigenetic effects alter the accessibility of DNA to proteins and so modulate transcription.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In eukaryotes the structure of chromatin, controlled by the histone code, regulates access to DNA with significant impacts on the expression of genes in euchromatin and heterochromatin areas.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Gene expression in mammals is regulated by many cis-regulatory elements, including core promoters and promoter-proximal elements that are located near the transcription start sites of genes, upstream on the DNA (towards the 5' region of the sense strand).
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Other important cis-regulatory modules are localized in DNA regions that are distant from the transcription start sites.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] These include enhancers, silencers, insulators and tethering elements.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Enhancers and their associated transcription factors have a leading role in the regulation of gene expression.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Enhancers are genome regions that regulate genes.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Enhancers control cell-type-specific gene expression programs, most often by looping through long distances to come in physical proximity with the promoters of their target genes.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Multiple enhancers, each often tens or hundred of thousands of nucleotides distant from their target genes, loop to their target gene promoters and coordinate with each other to control gene expression.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The illustration shows an enhancer looping around to come into proximity with the promoter of a target gene.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The loop is stabilized by a dimer of a connector protein (e.g. dimer of CTCF or YY1).
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] One member of the dimer is anchored to its binding motif on the enhancer and the other member is anchored to its binding motif on the promoter (represented by the red zigzags in the illustration).
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Several cell function-specific transcription factors (among the about 1,600 transcription factors in a human cell) generally bind to specific motifs on an enhancer.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] A small combination of these enhancer-bound transcription factors, when brought close to a promoter by a DNA loop, govern transcription level of the target gene.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Mediator (a complex usually consisting of about 26 proteins in an interacting structure) communicates regulatory signals from enhancer DNA-bound transcription factors directly to the RNA polymerase II (pol II) enzyme bound to the promoter.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Enhancers, when active, are generally transcribed from both strands of DNA with RNA polymerases acting in two different directions, producing two eRNAs as illustrated in the figure.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] An inactive enhancer may be bound by an inactive transcription factor.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Phosphorylation of the transcription factor may activate it and that activated transcription factor may then activate the enhancer to which it is bound (see small red star representing phosphorylation of transcription factor bound to enhancer in the illustration).
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] An activated enhancer begins transcription of its RNA before activating transcription of messenger RNA from its target gene.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] DNA methylation is a widespread mechanism for epigenetic influence on gene expression and is seen in bacteria and eukaryotes and has roles in heritable transcription silencing and transcription regulation.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Methylation most often occurs on a cytosine (see Figure).
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Methylation of cytosine primarily occurs in dinucleotide sequences where a cytosine is followed by a guanine, a CpG site.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The number of CpG sites in the human genome is about 28 million.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Depending on the type of cell, about 70% of the CpG sites have a methylated cytosine.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Methylation of cytosine in DNA has a major role in regulating gene expression.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Methylation of CpGs in a promoter region of a gene usually represses gene transcription while methylation of CpGs in the body of a gene increases expression.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] TET enzymes play a central role in demethylation of methylated cytosines.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Demethylation of CpGs in a gene promoter by TET enzyme activity increases transcription of the gene.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In eukaryotes, where export of RNA is required before translation is possible, nuclear export is thought to provide additional control over gene expression.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] All transport in and out of the nucleus is via the nuclear pore and transport is controlled by a wide range of importin and exportin proteins.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Expression of a gene coding for a protein is only possible if the messenger RNA carrying the code survives long enough to be translated.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In a typical cell, an RNA molecule is only stable if specifically protected from degradation.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] RNA degradation has particular importance in regulation of expression in eukaryotic cells where mRNA has to travel significant distances before being translated.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In eukaryotes, RNA is stabilised by certain post-transcriptional modifications, particularly the 5′ cap and poly-adenylated tail.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Intentional degradation of mRNA is used not just as a defence mechanism from foreign RNA (normally from viruses) but also as a route of mRNA *destabilisation*.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] If an mRNA molecule has a complementary sequence to a small interfering RNA then it is targeted for destruction via the RNA interference pathway.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Three prime untranslated regions (3′UTRs) of messenger RNAs (mRNAs) often contain regulatory sequences that post-transcriptionally influence gene expression.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Such 3′-UTRs often contain both binding sites for microRNAs (miRNAs) as well as for regulatory proteins.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] By binding to specific sites within the 3′-UTR, miRNAs can decrease gene expression of various mRNAs by either inhibiting translation or directly causing degradation of the transcript.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The 3′-UTR also may have silencer regions that bind repressor proteins that inhibit the expression of a mRNA.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The 3′-UTR often contains microRNA response elements (MREs).
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] MREs are sequences to which miRNAs bind.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] These are prevalent motifs within 3′-UTRs.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Among all regulatory motifs within the 3′-UTRs (e.g. including silencer regions), MREs make up about half of the motifs.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] As of 2014, the miRBase web site, an archive of miRNA sequences and annotations, listed 28,645 entries in 233 biologic species.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Of these, 1,881 miRNAs were in annotated human miRNA loci. miRNAs were predicted to have an average of about four hundred target mRNAs (affecting expression of several hundred genes).
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Friedman et al. estimate that >45,000 miRNA target sites within human mRNA 3′UTRs are conserved above background levels, and >60% of human protein-coding genes have been under selective pressure to maintain pairing to miRNAs.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Direct experiments show that a single miRNA can reduce the stability of hundreds of unique mRNAs.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Other experiments show that a single miRNA may repress the production of hundreds of proteins, but that this repression often is relatively mild (less than 2-fold).
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The effects of miRNA dysregulation of gene expression seem to be important in cancer.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] For instance, in gastrointestinal cancers, nine miRNAs have been identified as epigenetically altered and effective in down regulating DNA repair enzymes.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The effects of miRNA dysregulation of gene expression also seem to be important in neuropsychiatric disorders, such as schizophrenia, bipolar disorder, major depression, Parkinson's disease, Alzheimer's disease and autism spectrum disorders.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Direct regulation of translation is less prevalent than control of transcription or mRNA stability but is occasionally used.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Inhibition of protein translation is a major target for toxins and antibiotics, so they can kill a cell by overriding its normal gene expression control.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Protein synthesis inhibitors include the antibiotic neomycin and the toxin ricin.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Post-translational modifications (PTMs) are covalent modifications to proteins.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Like RNA splicing, they help to significantly diversify the proteome.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] These modifications are usually catalyzed by enzymes.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Additionally, processes like covalent additions to amino acid side chain residues can often be reversed by other enzymes.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] However, some, like the proteolytic cleavage of the protein backbone, are irreversible.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] PTMs play many important roles in the cell.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] For example, phosphorylation is primarily involved in activating and deactivating proteins and in signaling pathways.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] PTMs are involved in transcriptional regulation: an important function of acetylation and methylation is histone tail modification, which alters how accessible DNA is for transcription.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] They can also be seen in the immune system, where glycosylation plays a key role.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] One type of PTM can initiate another type of PTM, as can be seen in how ubiquitination tags proteins for degradation through proteolysis.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Proteolysis, other than being involved in breaking down proteins, is also important in activating and deactivating them, and in regulating biological processes such as DNA transcription and cell death.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Measuring gene expression is an important part of many life sciences, as the ability to quantify the level at which a particular gene is expressed within a cell, tissue or organism can provide a lot of valuable information.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Similarly, the analysis of the location of protein expression is a powerful tool, and this can be done on an organismal or cellular scale.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Investigation of localization is particularly important for the study of development in multicellular organisms and as an indicator of protein function in single cells.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Ideally, measurement of expression is done by detecting the final gene product (for many genes, this is the protein); however, it is often easier to detect one of the precursors, typically mRNA and to infer gene-expression levels from these measurements.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Levels of mRNA can be quantitatively measured by northern blotting, which provides size and sequence information about the mRNA molecules.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] A sample of RNA is separated on an agarose gel and hybridized to a radioactively labeled RNA probe that is complementary to the target sequence.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The radiolabeled RNA is then detected by an autoradiograph.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Because the use of radioactive reagents makes the procedure time-consuming and potentially dangerous, alternative labeling and detection methods, such as digoxigenin and biotin chemistries, have been developed.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Perceived disadvantages of Northern blotting are that large quantities of RNA are required and that quantification may not be completely accurate, as it involves measuring band strength in an image of a gel.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] On the other hand, the additional mRNA size information from the Northern blot allows the discrimination of alternately spliced transcripts.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Another approach for measuring mRNA abundance is RT-qPCR.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] In this technique, reverse transcription is followed by quantitative PCR.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Reverse transcription first generates a DNA template from the mRNA; this single-stranded template is called cDNA.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The cDNA template is then amplified in the quantitative step, during which the fluorescence emitted by labeled hybridization probes or intercalating dyes changes as the DNA amplification process progresses.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] For expression profiling, or high-throughput analysis of many genes within a sample, quantitative PCR may be performed for hundreds of genes simultaneously in the case of low-density arrays.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] A second approach is the hybridization microarray.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] A single array or "chip" may contain probes to determine transcript levels for every known gene in the genome of one or more organisms.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Alternatively, "tag based" technologies like Serial analysis of gene expression (SAGE) and RNA-Seq, which can provide a relative measure of the cellular concentration of different mRNAs, can be used.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] An advantage of tag-based methods is the "open architecture", allowing for the exact measurement of any transcript, with a known or unknown sequence.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Next-generation sequencing (NGS) such as RNA-Seq is another approach, producing vast quantities of sequence data that can be matched to a reference genome.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Although NGS is comparatively time-consuming, expensive, and resource-intensive, it can identify single-nucleotide polymorphisms, splice-variants, and novel genes, and can also be used to profile expression in organisms for which little or no sequence information is available.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] For genes encoding proteins, the expression level can be directly assessed by a number of methods with some clear analogies to the techniques for mRNA quantification.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] One of the most commonly used methods is to perform a Western blot against the protein of interest.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] This gives information on the size of the protein in addition to its identity.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] A sample (often cellular lysate) is separated on a polyacrylamide gel, transferred to a membrane and then probed with an antibody to the protein of interest.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The antibody can either be conjugated to a fluorophore or to horseradish peroxidase for imaging and/or quantification.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The gel-based nature of this assay makes quantification less accurate, but it has the advantage of being able to identify later modifications to the protein, for example proteolysis or ubiquitination, from changes in size.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] While transcription directly reflects gene expression, the copy number of mRNA molecules does not directly correlate with the number of protein molecules translated from mRNA.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Quantification of both protein and mRNA permits a correlation of the two levels.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Regulation on each step of gene expression can impact the correlation, as shown for regulation of translation or protein stability.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Post-translational factors, such as protein transport in highly polar cells, can influence the measured mRNA-protein correlation as well.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Analysis of expression is not limited to quantification; localization can also be determined. mRNA can be detected with a suitably labelled complementary mRNA strand and protein can be detected via labelled antibodies.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The probed sample is then observed by microscopy to identify where the mRNA or protein is.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] By replacing the gene with a new version fused to a green fluorescent protein marker or similar, expression may be directly quantified in live cells.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] This is done by imaging using a fluorescence microscope.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] It is very difficult to clone a GFP-fused protein into its native location in the genome without affecting expression levels, so this method often cannot be used to measure endogenous gene expression.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] It is, however, widely used to measure the expression of a gene artificially introduced into the cell, for example via an expression vector.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] By fusing a target protein to a fluorescent reporter, the protein's behavior, including its cellular localization and expression level, can be significantly changed.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay works by using antibodies immobilised on a microtiter plate to capture proteins of interest from samples added to the well.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] Using a detection antibody conjugated to an enzyme or fluorophore the quantity of bound protein can be accurately measured by fluorometric or colourimetric detection.
[src:gene-expression/gene-expression] The detection process is very similar to that of a Western blot, but by avoiding the gel steps more accurate quantification can be achieved.
